Chrysippus. —Finally, it can be shown that the remarks on the education of children (ch. 28 f.) are not wholly origi- nal with the youthful author, but have been largely influ- enced, directly or indirectly, by an exhaustive and popular treatise on this subject by the celebrated Stoio Chrysippus which bore the title περὶ παίδων ἀγωγῆς. umber ἀγωγῆς, and the Dialogus coincide so frequently, even in the phraseology, as pointed out in the Notos, that the conclusion of their common indebtedness to the Stoic's trea tiso—for they are independent of one another-becomes irresistible.l

But, however extensive the obligations of the author to previous writers, notably Cicero, may have been, we cannot butconoede that Tacitus, even in this treatise of his youth, was no slavish imitator, but that he assimilated his horrowed material in so thorough a manner, as to make it virtually his own, thus succeeding in producing abrilliant work, Ι dramatis in construction, artistically elaborated in style and substance, and, in consequence, bearing all the outward in- dications oi an original composition.
